  "narrative": "<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Short impact summary</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The article \"OER by Discipline Guide: Reducing Barriers and Building Sustainability for OER Adoption\" highlights the efforts towards enhancing the adoption and sustainability of Open Educational Resources (OER) within various academic disciplines. Published in Open MIND in 2023 by authors Sarah Adams and Savannah Sillito, the work aims to address existing barriers and promote a collaborative framework for OER integration. Despite the absence of citations and mentions in popular discourse, the research contributes to ongoing discussions within the academic community about the importance of accessible educational materials.</p>\n<h3 class=\"story-subheading\">Full narrative</h3>\n<p class=\"story-text\">The 2023 article titled \"OER by Discipline Guide: Reducing Barriers and Building Sustainability for OER Adoption,\" authored by Sarah Adams and Savannah Sillito and published in Open MIND, provides a valuable resource in the realm of Open Educational Resources (OER). The authors aim to facilitate a greater understanding of the challenges associated with OER implementation across different academic disciplines. While the metrics indicate a lack of citations and public discourse, the publication remains an important step toward fostering a culture of open access in education.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">This work addresses significant hurdles that educators and institutions face when trying to incorporate OER into their teaching practices. By identifying these barriers and proposing strategies for overcoming them, the article sets a foundation for future research and practical applications in the field. The absence of community engagement metrics might suggest a need for increased outreach and awareness, signaling an opportunity for the authors to share their findings more broadly within educational circles.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Additionally, the article emphasizes the need for sustainability in OER efforts, a critical component in ensuring that educational resources remain relevant and accessible. As the academic landscape continues to shift toward more inclusive practices, the work of Adams and Sillito serves as a reference point for scholars and practitioners advocating for the expanded use of OER. This focus on sustainability aligns with global educational trends aiming to improve equity in learning environments.</p>\n<p class=\"story-text\">Overall, while the current impact metrics indicate minimal engagement and recognition, it is essential to consider this publication as part of ongoing conversations about educational resource accessibility. The authors' insights could pave the way for subsequent studies and initiatives, reinforcing the importance of open education in fostering a more equitable academic community. Future research could build upon the foundation laid in this article, exploring the effectiveness of proposed solutions and further engaging with the academic community to amplify the discussion surrounding OER adoption.</p>",
